Sales of new, single-family homesfell 14.9 pct in May from April to a seasonally adjusted annualrate of 616,000 units, the Commerce Department said.    The department revised April sales downward to show a 1.0pct increase from March to 724,000 units instead of thepreviously reported 7.6 pct gain.    Last month's drop was the biggest since January, 1982, whensales fell 19.5 pct and brought the level of sales to itslowest point since December, 1984, when 597,000 units weresold, the department said.    Home sales in May were 20.7 pct below the May, 1986, levelof 777,000, the department said.    Before seasonal adjustment, the number of homes actuallysold in May totaled 58,000, down from 71,000 in April and75,000 in May a year ago.    The average price was 129,600 dlrs in May, up from 117,500dlrs in April and 114,600 dlrs in May, 1986.    The median price was 106,800 dlrs, up from 97,900 dlrs inApril and 92,100 dlrs in May a year ago. Reuter&#3;